ombrowicz masked his attraction to men in his works, keeping the truth hidden in an intimate diary; Pereleshin explored his lust in Brazilian Portuguese after being shunned by the Russian diaspora; Taïa writes in French to destabilize both the language and his status as an immigrant in France; Mogutin becomes a hardcore gay rebel in word and image to rattle assumptions about gay life.Bringing authors generally not familiar to an English-speaking readership into one volume, and including Beaudoin's own experience of living between languages, Lost and Found Voices provides provocative insights into what it means to be gay in both the past and the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay authorsxSocial conditions. 0aGay menxIntellectual life. 0aGay menxSocial conditions. 0aGay people's writingsxHistory and criticism. 0aGay political refugeesxIntellectual life. 0aGay political refugeesxSocial conditions. 0aGays' writingsxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh  aAbdellah Taia.  aAriel.  aBrazilian.  aFerdydurke.  aFrench.  aIaroslav.  aKronos.  aLa vie lente.  aMaghreb.  aMoroccan.  aNovel German.  aRoman s nemtsem.  aRomance.  aRussian writers.  aSlava.  aSlow Life.  aTrans-Atlantyk.  aValerii Pereleshin.  aValerio.  aValery.  aWitold Gombrowicz.  aYaroslav Mogutin.  aauthorial voice.  aexile.  agay.  ahomosexuality.  aimmigrant.  aliterature.  apoems.  apoetry.  aqueer.  atranslation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228014812?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228014812